How to push/pull files to/from Github

  1. Open the project. Eitherâ¦.
  • Open an existing local repository on your computer : Open RStudio. Click on the the project button at the very upper left-hand corner of RStudio, click open project, find the location of the project on your computer, click the .Rproj file and open.
  • Or clone a repository on your local computer: start at step 2 above.

  1. In the âGitâ tab, click âPullâ. This will ensure the files on your computer is up to date with the ones on GitHub. If your files are up to date a message will display saying âAlready up to dateâ. If your files are behind what is on GitHub, it will update your local files and give you a list of the files it updated.

  2. Edit your files. Click âsaveâ to save them to your local computer (this does not save them to GitHub. )

  3. Commit your changes

    • select the check boxes to âstageâ the changesâ¦ only the files you select will be part of this commit
    • Select âCommitâ
    • A new window pops up where you should enter an informative commit message and look over the âDiffââ¦ if there were a previous committed version of the file, the Diff summarizes all changes since
    • Press âCommitâ

  4. Push your commits to GitHub. The changes arenât on GitHub until you PUSH them!!

  5. (Optional step I recommend) When you are done working on your current code project, close the project by clicking on the the project button at the very upper left-hand corner of RStudio, click close project. (This will ensure any code you do from here on out does not affect the .Rproj). The projects button should now say âProject (none)â. When you want to open this project back up, start back at step 10!

Repeat steps 10-15!
